   ((6)Sigma(+)) are determined. The force fields and spectroscopic
   parameters have been worked out from these analytical potential energy
   functions. For the ground state of CrH+, the calculated results of R-e,
   f(2), f(3), f(4), B-e, alpha(e), omega(e) and omega(e)chi(e), are
   0.16200 nm, 1.52574 aJ/nm(2), -7.81171 aJ/nm(3), 28.61613 aJ/nm(4),
   6.71181, 0.28792, 1624.6297 and 53.55394 cm(-1), respectively; and for
   the ground state of CrH, the corresponding parameters are 0.24005 nm,
   0.42946 aJ/nm(2), -0.97766 aJ/nm(3), 2.40438 aJ/nm(4), 2.9562, 0.050184,
   858.059 and 6.46813 cm(-1), respectively. The theoretical results show
   minimum points in the potential energy curves of CrH+ ((5)Sigma(+)) and
   CrH (X-6 Sigma(+)), so we conclude that CrH(X-6 Sigma(+))and CrH+
   ((5)Sigma(+)) are stable. But there are no minimum points in the
